We adjusted up the level in 1800 (vs. the level implied by Russia's growth rate) to avoid an implausibly low level in 1800 (below 340, which seem to contradict the description in general historical literature about the countries). The ranking of the republics were unchanged (vs. the level implied by Russia's growth rate).

We assumed the same level as in 1800 since the adjusted growth rate (1800-1960) would have been negative for 1800-1820. The level for 1800 remained as assumed, and the growth 1800-1960 were fitted to these two levels. The level in 1820 is the only one that deviates from this adjusted growth series.

column6: Growth from Maddison on line, adjusted to fit levels in 1800 and 1910. The original Maddison on-line series had no observation for 1800, but it had figures for earlier years. 1800 was hence based on an interpolation. This original growth series was then adjusted to fit the our new level in 1800. The choice of 1910 as the last year of the adjusted series was made ad-hoc.

Extrapolated, assuming zero growth 1600-1740. Assumption based on van Zanden (e1867) & Allen (e1856).

The level is based on the ratio of China at this time to the level of UK in 1800. The ratio is taken from van Zanden (e1867).  The level in 1800 for UK is based on the growth in 1800-2005 from Maddison on-line and the ICP benchmark, rather than the adjusted growth rates we use. The documentation explain the background fo this estimate in more detail.
column11: The UK data used for this ratio was the data in version 13 of the dataset (which used maddison on-line rather than Measuring Worth, as in version 14). However, the difference is 10%, at the most, which is within any reasonable error margin.

column9: We guesstimated the growth so that it would fit the levels in 1938 & 1945. The large (implied) drop between these two years are suspiciously large, eventhough the wars probably were bery devastating. We suspect that at least one of the estimates are in need of revision. We assumed a higher negative growth during the world war 2, and a somewhat lower negative growth during the civil war up to 1949 (this is only based on the fact that the causalities seem to have been much higher during the world war). We assume a tiny improvement between 1949 and 1950, since most of the fighting seem to have ended in 1949.

The reasons for this adjustment are: (a) e1868 concludes that real urban wages in Japan was on-par with the lagging parts of Europe. (b) e1870 suggest that agricultural production at the beginnning of the Meiji may be underestimated (and hence that the subsequent growth is somewhat overestimated). See documentation for details.

Guestimates that tried to make both the levels and movements reasonable, inlcuding the movements 1770-1820. We based the guestimates on a compromise of two sources: (1). E1793, model 1, have model-estimated the income ratio Turley/UK for six benchmark years 1500-1820. We multiplied this ratio with our level estimates for UK. However, e1793 cite reasons why the implied growth is too large. (2). E1843 gives a narrative for the income movements.

However, e1793 cite reasons why the implied growth is too large. (2). E1843 gives a narrative for the income movements.
